However, this is essentially where my mind goes...<br>
<br>
1) Iraq hates the US.  This is largely a result of Gulf War I where we booted his ass out of Kuwait.<br>
<br>
2) Saddam is vindictive and blind rage and a desire for revenge do motivate him.  For example, he tried to assassinate a former president who posed no threat to him at that point.<br>
<br>
3) Iraq has shown in the past that it desires to develop WMD, including nuclear weapons.  Look at the reactors that were being built for Iraq in the 1970's/80's (which Israel bombed) as well as the admissions of defected nuclear scientists.<br>
<br>
4) Al Qaeda hates the US and desires to see as many American civilians die as possible.  This is obvious.<br>
<br>
Given the above, I don't see it as that much of a stretch that unchecked, Saddam succeeds in developing nukes, teams up with Al Qaeda despite the fact that they are not great friends to strike a common enemy, and NYC or Washington DC goes up in a mushroom cloud.<br>
<br>
This may well make a lot of muslims hate us, but what scares me the most is the possibility of nuclear weapons in the hands of terrorists.  Bin Laden can't do that alone, he'd need a national level regime for it.<br>
